58b.clickbait: Root page for topics on logical decision theory, with multiple intros for different audiences.

5n9.title: Causal decision theories
5n9.clickbait: On CDT, to choose rationally, you should imagine the world where your physical act changes, then imagine running that world forward in time.  (Therefore, it's irrational to vote in elections.)

5pt.title: Newcomblike decision problems
5pt.clickbait: Decision problems in which your choice correlates with something other than its physical consequences (say, because somebody has predicted you very well) can do weird things to some decision theories.

5pv.title: Newcomb's Problem
5pv.clickbait: There are two boxes in front of you, Box A and Box B.  You can take both boxes, or only Box B.  Box A contains $1000.  Box B contains $1,000,000 if and only if Omega predicted you'd take only Box B.

5px.title: Evidential decision theories
5px.clickbait: Theories which hold that the principle of rational choice is "Choose the act that would be the best news, if somebody told you that you'd chosen that act."

5qn.title: Death in Damascus
5qn.clickbait: Death tells you that It is coming for you tomorrow.  You can stay in Damascus or flee to Aleppo.  Whichever decision you actually make is the wrong one.  This gives some decision theories trouble.

5rf.title: Toxoplasmosis dilemma
5rf.clickbait: A parasitic infection, carried by cats, may make humans enjoy petting cats more.  A kitten, now in front of you, isn't infected.  But if you *want* to pet it, you may already be infected.  Do you?
5rf.text:
The parasite [toxoplasma gondii](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toxoplasmosis) can be transmitted by cats and rats.  *Toxoplasma gondii* can pass from cat feces to rats.  Rats infected by *toxoplasma gondii* are less averse to cat odors, increasing the probability that they will be eaten by cats (which again transmits the parasite to cats).

*Toxoplasma gondii* can also be transmitted to humans, causing toxoplasmosis; the non-acute form of which is implicated in other problems like schizophrenia.

For a while, starting in 2011, it was thought that infection with *toxoplasma gondii* may also cause human beings to like cats more (the newspapers talked about "crazy cat lady syndrome").  More recently, these studies may have failed to replicate.  But this is sufficiently lovely for reformulating an old decision-theory problem that we're going to pretend otherwise.

Suppose the human toxoplasmosis studies had replicated.  In particular, suppose that in the following experiment...

- Subjects are told about the general existence of toxoplasmosis.
- Subjects are presented with a cute kitten that is guaranteed to not carry toxoplasmosis (or to present any other known health dangers).
- Subjects are offered a chance to pet the cute kitten.

...subjects who chose to pet the kitten were found to be 20% likely to have latent toxoplasmosis, while those who refrained from petting the kitten were 10% likely to have latent toxoplasmosis.

You are now part of a similar experiment.  If you pet the kitten, an observer would conclude that your absolute risk of latent toxoplasmosis is 10% higher, the health risks of which considerably outweigh the hedonic gains of petting the kitten.  (We could postulate perhaps that petting the kitten gains you 1,000 hedonic units, while having latent toxoplasmosis will cost you 10,000,000 hedonic units. %note: The relative quantities chosen to be similar to those in [5pv Newcomb's Problem].%)  On the other hand, petting the kitten cannot *cause* you to have toxoplasmosis--either you already have it or you don't.  Do you pet the kitten?

[todo: insert causal diagram here]

This dilemma, in the forms of the structurally similar [solomons_problem Solomon's Problem] and [smoking_lesion the Smoking Lesion], were historically significant in the invention of [5n9 causal decision theory] and its widespread adoption over the alternative of [5px evidential decision theory].  (The Toxoplasmosis Dilemma has a more realistic causal structure than [solomons_problem Solomon's Problem] and [smoking_lesion the Smoking Lesion], which might otherwise confuse the unfamiliar reader.)

# Analysis

## Causal decision theory



## Evidential decision theory

## Evidential decision theory with a tickle defense

We can suppose perhaps that in a study *without* the subjects being told about toxoplasmosis, almost everyone decided to pet the kitten--so just noticing that you want to pet the kitten isn't enough to tell you the answer already.

  Still, this sounds a bit like either evidential decision theorists are more likely to get toxoplasmosis, or toxoplasmosis causes people to be evidential decision theorists.  Otherwise observing your own impulses *and* observing yourself to be an evidential decision theorist with a tickle defense, ought to screen off the answer--people like that either pet cats or they don't.



## Logical decision theory

Intuitively, a logical decision theory would reply that you can't make yourself not have toxoplasmosis if you didn't pet the kitten.  In the counterfactual alternative where LDT agents output an answer of "don't pet the kitten", we would find a world where fewer people petted kittens and the correlation between toxoplasmosis and kitten-petting was weaker, not a world where this particular LDT agent had a lower chance of toxoplasmosis.

Even so, if the situation is truly analogous between this agent and the experimental agent, an LDT agent wants to know where this correlation came from in the first place.
